<paragraph id="8BF7A224FFBAB825FF674FE06420F822" blockId="13.[151,1436,1601,1985]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">
<emphasis id="B93C7E36FFBAB825FF674FE06700F925" bold="true" box="[199,564,1709,1734]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">ADULT FEMALE. Diagnosis.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="4C48D9A7FFBAB825FDE04FE36604F926" authorityName="Kaydan &amp; Gullan" authorityYear="2012" box="[576,816,1709,1733]" class="Insecta" family="Pseudococcidae" genus="Ferrisia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="colombiana">
<emphasis id="B93C7E36FFBAB825FDE04FE36604F926" box="[576,816,1709,1733]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Ferrisia colombiana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be diagnosed by the following combination of features: absence of clusters of small oral-collar tubular ducts on ventral margins of abdominal segments; ventral oral-collar tubular ducts generally associated with 1 or 2 discoidal pores on derm around duct rim, each pore 4–5 µm in diameter and almost two times larger than duct opening; dorsal enlarged tubular ducts totalling 10–29 throughout dorsum, rim of each duct with 1 or 2 oval discoidal pores (sometimes 2 pores almost merged) usually associated with duct opening; number of multilocular disc pores on venter of abdominal segments as follows: V (0 or 1), VI (6–10), VII (14–22), and VIII + IX (8–14); both pairs of ostioles present and well developed.
</paragraph>
<caption id="DF37F2ACFFB9B826FF374EEF66B3F85B" box="[151,903,1954,1977]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" startId="14.[151,250,1954,1977]" targetBox="[203,1381,200,1925]" targetPageId="14">
<paragraph id="8BF7A224FFB9B826FF374EEF66B3F85B" blockId="14.[151,903,1954,1977]" box="[151,903,1954,1977]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">
<emphasis id="B93C7E36FFB9B826FF374EEF6426F85A" bold="true" box="[151,274,1954,1977]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">FIGURE 6.</emphasis>
Adult female of 
<taxonomicName id="4C48D9A7FFB9B826FE1F4EEE667FF85B" authority="Kaydan &amp; Gullan" authorityName="Kaydan &amp; Gullan" authorityYear="2012" box="[447,843,1954,1976]" class="Insecta" family="Pseudococcidae" genus="Ferrisia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="colombiana" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis id="B93C7E36FFB9B826FE1F4EEE67A5F85B" box="[447,657,1954,1976]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">Ferrisia colombiana</emphasis>
Kaydan &amp; Gullan
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A20FC34DFFB9B826FCF14EEE66B3F85B" box="[849,903,1955,1976]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" rank="species">sp. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph id="8BF7A224FFB8B827FF6749D5647AFE4F" blockId="15.[151,1440,151,1615]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">
<taxonomicName id="4C48D9A7FFB8B827FF6749D5649AFF53" authorityName="Kaydan &amp; Gullan" authorityYear="2012" box="[199,430,152,176]" class="Insecta" family="Pseudococcidae" genus="Ferrisia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="colombiana">
<emphasis id="B93C7E36FFB8B827FF6749D5649AFF53" box="[199,430,152,176]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Ferrisia colombiana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be readily distinguished from other species in the genus by having a small number of enlarged dorsal tubular ducts; lacking clusters of small marginal oral-collar tubular ducts; having large discodial pores associated with the ventral oral-collar tubular ducts; and by the presence of multilocular disc pores on abdominal segment VI. 
<taxonomicName id="4C48D9A7FFB8B827FE06484867BAFEFF" authorityName="Kaydan &amp; Gullan" authorityYear="2012" box="[422,654,260,284]" class="Insecta" family="Pseudococcidae" genus="Ferrisia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="colombiana">
<emphasis id="B93C7E36FFB8B827FE06484867BAFEFF" box="[422,654,260,284]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Ferrisia colombiana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is most similar to 
<taxonomicName id="4C48D9A7FFB8B827FCC1484866DFFEFF" authorityName="Kaydan &amp; Gullan" authorityYear="2012" box="[865,1003,261,284]" class="Insecta" family="Pseudococcidae" genus="Ferrisia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pitcairnia">
<emphasis id="B93C7E36FFB8B827FCC1484866DFFEFF" box="[865,1003,261,284]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">F. pitcairnia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but the adult female of 
<taxonomicName id="4C48D9A7FFB8B827FB5C484860A8FEFF" authorityName="Kaydan &amp; Gullan" authorityYear="2012" box="[1276,1436,260,284]" class="Insecta" family="Pseudococcidae" genus="Ferrisia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="colombiana">
<emphasis id="B93C7E36FFB8B827FB5C484860A8FEFF" box="[1276,1436,260,284]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">F. colombiana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is usually much larger than those of 
<taxonomicName id="4C48D9A7FFB8B827FDC1486467C6FEDC" authorityName="Kaydan &amp; Gullan" authorityYear="2012" box="[609,754,296,320]" class="Insecta" family="Pseudococcidae" genus="Ferrisia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pitcairnia">
<emphasis id="B93C7E36FFB8B827FDC1486467C6FEDC" box="[609,754,296,320]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">F. pitcairnia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and slide-mounted specimens of 
<taxonomicName id="4C48D9A7FFB8B827FB364864600AFEA3" authorityName="Kaydan &amp; Gullan" authorityYear="2012" box="[1174,1342,296,320]" class="Insecta" family="Pseudococcidae" genus="Ferrisia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="colombiana">
<emphasis id="B93C7E36FFB8B827FB364864600AFEA3" box="[1174,1342,296,320]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">F. colombiana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be distinguished readily from 
<taxonomicName id="4C48D9A7FFB8B827FE784800675CFE87" authorityName="Kaydan &amp; Gullan" authorityYear="2012" box="[472,616,333,356]" class="Insecta" family="Pseudococcidae" genus="Ferrisia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pitcairnia">
<emphasis id="B93C7E36FFB8B827FE784800675CFE87" box="[472,616,333,356]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">F. pitcairnia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the presence of translucent pores on the hind legs (absent in 
<taxonomicName id="4C48D9A7FFB8B827FA2748006431FE64" authorityName="Kaydan &amp; Gullan" authorityYear="2012" class="Insecta" family="Pseudococcidae" genus="Ferrisia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pitcairnia">
<emphasis id="B93C7E36FFB8B827FA2748006431FE64" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">F. pitcairnia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) and by having a higher number of ventral oral-collar tubular ducts (
<quantity id="4CB00FC1FFB8B827FBB148226142FE64" box="[1041,1142,367,391]" metricMagnitude="0" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.7018" metricValueMax="1.905" metricValueMin="1.4986" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" unit="in" value="67.0" valueMax="75.0" valueMin="59.0">59–75 in</quantity>
<taxonomicName id="4C48D9A7FFB8B827FBDE483C602AFE6B" authorityName="Kaydan &amp; Gullan" authorityYear="2012" box="[1150,1310,368,392]" class="Insecta" family="Pseudococcidae" genus="Ferrisia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="colombiana">
<emphasis id="B93C7E36FFB8B827FBDE483C602AFE6B" box="[1150,1310,368,392]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">F. colombiana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<quantity id="4CB00FC1FFB8B827FAF648226599FE4F" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.826" metricValueMax="5.842" metricValueMin="3.81" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" unit="in" value="19.0" valueMax="23.0" valueMin="15.0">15–23 in</quantity>
<taxonomicName id="4C48D9A7FFB8B827FF1448D86409FE4F" authorityName="Kaydan &amp; Gullan" authorityYear="2012" box="[180,317,405,428]" class="Insecta" family="Pseudococcidae" genus="Ferrisia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pitcairnia">
<emphasis id="B93C7E36FFB8B827FF1448D86409FE4F" box="[180,317,405,428]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">F. pitcairnia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
